Reasoning: The solution is functionally correct: the algorithm returns characters with maximum frequency ordered by their last occurrences, and I validated it by running deterministic examples and a brute-force verifier across 1000 random tests plus long and edge-case tests (all passed). Style is decent in the core function (a brief explanatory comment) but the file contains many unnecessary wildcard and duplicate imports and noisy boilerplate, which hurts readability. Simplicity and robustness are good because the core logic is O(n) and concise and it handled all tested edge cases; however the excessive imports and lack of explicit handling for an empty input (outside constraints) reduce maintainability.
